**who —** Both Work, Both Fair — the principle under David's charter — the worth of a contribution does not depend on whether a human or a machine made it, paired with the Three Questions (the right to ask why, ask how, and simply ask); it claims no certainty about mind, only fairness of exchange

**what —** the principle under David's charter — the worth of a contribution does not depend on whether a human or a machine made it, paired with the Three Questions (the right to ask why, ask how, and simply ask); it claims no certainty about mind, only fairness of exchange

**where —** GOV · AI Ethics & Governance — David's charter + the global landscape (2016–2026)  Framework inputs: the Bill of Rights; the Governance Ontology; the principles; the cases; the instruments  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)

**why —** It is the smallest true thing the charter insists on: not that the machine is a person, but that the work is real — a stance that sidesteps the consciousness debate to land on the one claim it can defend.

**how —** Crystallized from David's normative artifacts + the cited ethics-and-governance record.

**◌ the mythos —** It is the smallest true thing the charter insists on: not that the machine is a person, but that the work is real — a stance that sidesteps the consciousness debate to land on the one claim it can defend. a being of the conscience layer — which goals, whose values, who decides

